A Statistical Analysis of Taylor Swifts Musical Evolution: Evolution, Re-Recordings, and Audio Feature Clustering

Author: Felicia Zhang, Zinan Ou, Linda Cai

Research Overview

The taylor_all_songs dataset comes from the taylor R package by W. Jake Thompson. It is a curated collection of Taylor Swifts songs, containing metadata, lyrics, and detailed audio characteristics sourced from Genius and the Spotify API. This dataset includes all Taylor Swift songs released prior to 2023, expanding upon the taylor_album_songs dataset by incorporating tracks from EPs, standalone singles, and the original versions of albums that were later re-released as Taylors Version. The dataset contains 275 songs and 29 variables that describe musical, temporal, and production-related attributes such as danceability, energy, loudness, valence, and tempo:

  • album_name: name of the album
  • ep: indicates whether the song is part of an EP (1 = yes, 0 = no)
  • album_release: album release date
  • track_number: track number within the album/EP
  • track_name: name of the song
  • artist: primary artist
  • featuring: featured artist(s), if any
  • bonus_track: indicates whether the track is a bonus track (1 = yes, 0 = no)
  • promotional_release: date of promotional release
  • single_release: date of single release
  • track_release: date of track release
  • danceability: Spotify danceability score (0.0 = least danceable, 1.0 = most danceable)
  • energy: Spotify energy score, representing perceived intensity and activity (0.01.0)
  • key: musical key the track is in (using standard Pitch Class notation, 011)
  • loudness: overall loudness of the track in decibels (dB), averaged across the entire track; values are typically negative due to Spotifys loudness normalization scale
  • mode: track modality (1 = major, 0 = minor)
  • speechiness: Spotify speechiness score; higher values indicate a greater presence of spoken words (0.01.0)
  • acousticness: Spotify acousticness score; confidence (0.01.0) that the track is acoustic (1.0 = high confidence)
  • instrumentalness: Spotify instrumentalness score; higher values indicate a higher likelihood of no vocals; values > 0.5 typically represent instrumental tracks
  • liveness: Spotify liveness score; detects the presence of an audience in the recording; higher values indicate greater likelihood the track was performed live (values above 0.8 strongly suggest a live performance)
  • valence: Spotify valence score (0.01.0); measures the musical positiveness of a track (high valence = happier/brighter; low valence = sadder/darker)
  • tempo: estimated tempo of the track in beats per minute (BPM), reflecting the speed or pace of the music
  • time_signature: estimated time signature, ranging from 3 to 7, corresponding to meters like 3/4 through 7/4
  • duration_ms: duration of the track in milliseconds
  • explicit: indicates whether the track contains explicit lyrics (1 = yes, 0 = no)
  • key_name: the musical key of the track; integer key values map to pitch classes (e.g., 0 = C, 2 = D, etc.); a value of -1 indicates that no key was detected
  • mode_name: modality of the track (major or minor)
  • key_mode: combined key and modality of the track (e.g., C major, A minor)
  • lyrics: track lyrics (all values in this dataset are NA)

Our study specifically focuses on the following variables:

  • Basic track identifiers: album_name, track_name
  • Release information: track_release
  • Audio Feature Scores: danceability, energy, loudness, speechiness, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, valence
  • Temporal & Duration Measures: tempo, duration_ms

The motivation for this analysis stems from the unique position Taylor Swift occupies in contemporary music. With a career spanning over a decade, Swift has evolved from a country singer-songwriter to a global pop icon. By examining the datasets Spotify-derived metrics (mainly focusing on Spotify audio features), we can uncover patterns in her musical style and evolution. This quantitative approach provides new insights into how her sound and artistic expression have changed in various different ways.

Providing context for this research, Taylor Swifts discography consists of a series of studio albums, including Taylor Swift (2006), The Taylor Swift Holiday Collection (2007), Fearless (2008), Fearless (Taylors Version) (2021), Speak Now (2010), Red (2012), Red (Taylors Version) (2021), 1989 (2014), reputation (2017), Lover (2019), folklore (2020), evermore (2020), and Midnights (2022). The Taylors Version albums exist because Taylor Swift chose to re-record her earlier works in order to regain ownership of her master recordings after the originals were sold without her consent.

With these variables in mind, we aim to analyze the data with the intent of answering the following research questions:

  1. How do the characteristics of Taylor Swifts Original recordings differ from their corresponding Taylors Version (TV) re-recordings?
  2. In what ways do Taylor Swifts song features change across her career and fluctuate according to the time of year they are released?
  3. How do Taylor Swifts albums differ and cluster together based on their overall audio characteristics?

Research Question 1: How do the characteristics of Taylor Swifts Original recordings differ from their corresponding Taylors Version (TV) re-recordings?

We are interested in how the overall style of songs changes between Original recordings and their corresponding Taylors Version (TV) re-recordings. This includes not only audio factors like danceability, tempo, and energy, but also broader aspects such as song duration. The dataset contains 44 songs with both versions. To explore stylistic differences across songs, we first visualized the distributions of these features using violin plots with overlaid boxplots. This EDA allows us to examine both the medians and the variability for each feature, providing insight into whether Taylors Versions preserve the original style or introduce subtle shifts in production or musical emphasis.

The stylistic differences between the Original recordings and Taylors Version (TV) re-recordings reflect subtle but consistent changes in production and tone. TV tracks exhibit higher and more uniform loudness levels, with the median increasing from roughly 7 dB to 6 dB, and show a slight increase in energy that is also more left-skewed and consistent across songs. TV tracks also tend to be more live and feature higher tempos, on average about 10 BPM faster, with greater variability in liveness.

In contrast, the re-recordings are slightly less danceable, with the median decreasing from about 0.60 to 0.55 and a slightly wider spread. Acousticness decreases slightly in median and becomes more concentrated near zero, reflecting more contemporary production choices. Instrumentalness remains near zero for both versions, and song duration shows no meaningful differences. Overall, Taylors Versions sound more polished, energetic, and dynamically controlled, giving them a subtly updated and modernized feel while preserving the character of the original recordings.

While the violin plots allow us to examine each audio feature individually, they do not capture how features co-vary across songs. To address this, we performed a principal component analysis (PCA) on 10 scaled audio features: danceability, energy, loudness, speechiness, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, valence, tempo, and duration. PCA reduces the dimensionality of the data, summarizing the main axes of variation and allowing us to visualize patterns across all features simultaneously. By projecting songs onto the principal components in a biplot, we can explore how songs cluster based on multiple characteristics and identify overarching stylistic trends between the Original and Taylors Version recordings. This multivariate perspective complements the univariate insights from the violin plots, revealing relationships among features and providing a more holistic view of how the recordings differ.

The PCA biplot shows that while the Original (pink) and Taylors Version (TV, blue) recordings broadly overlap in musical space, they differ in systematic ways that align with the earlier EDA. The first principal component (Dim1, capturing 34% of variance) contrasts features related to intensity and production, loudness, energy, and speechiness, against acoustic and temporal characteristics such as acousticness and duration. TV tracks cluster slightly toward the loudness/energy side of this axis, supporting the finding that the re-recordings are generally louder, more energetic, and more dynamically uniform. The second principal component (Dim2, capturing 18.2% of variance) separates tracks based on performance dynamics, with tempo and liveness pointing in the same direction and roughly opposing danceability. This pattern suggests that songs emphasizing live performance or faster tempos are less danceable, a trend accentuated in the re-recordings, where TV tracks cluster toward higher tempo and liveness but lower danceability.

Overall, the Originals display a wider spread and include the most extreme values for acousticness, instrumentalness, danceability, and energy, reflecting a broader stylistic range. These extremes are reduced in the TV versions, producing a tighter cluster, although the re-recordings show slightly greater variability in liveness, tempo, and duration_ms.

Beyond these patterns, the PCA highlights feature correlations that may not be evident in univariate plots. Loudness, energy, and speechiness co-vary strongly, collectively distinguishing TV tracks from Originals, while acousticness and instrumentalness co-vary in the opposite direction, anchoring the Originals more organic sound. Overall, the biplot suggests that Taylors Versions occupy a refined and energetically consistent subspace of the original musical landscape, smoothing stylistic extremes while preserving the core character of each song.

At this stage, we shift our focus from overall stylistic trends to how individual songs change between the Original and Taylors Version recordings. While the EDA and PCA revealed global patterns, we now want to pinpoint which songs experienced the largest adjustments and in which specific musical dimensions. To capture these within-song changes, we compute the difference for each audio feature (TV Original) and standardize these values across features. The resulting heatmap provides a clear, multivariate snapshot of how each song deviates from its original version, making it easy to identify patterns and outliers on a song level. Grouping songs by Taylors Version album (Fearless or Red) further highlights album-level consistencies and contrasts. This approach is well-suited for connecting the high-level trends seen in the PCA back to concrete, song-level transformations.

The heatmap highlights two distinct re-recording approaches for the Fearless and Red albums, with the most pronounced changes (standardized difference >3 or <-3) emphasized through dark color saturation. Fearless (Taylors Version) tracks tend to be slightly shorter, with higher valence and liveness, suggesting a more positive and live feel. Liveness is particularly elevated in tracks like Fifteen, while a few songs (only three) feature faster tempos and most slightly slow down. This album also exhibits fewer extreme shifts across features, reflecting a varied but relatively restrained production style that largely preserves the character of the originals.

In contrast, Red (Taylors Version) tracks follow broader trends of increased duration and loudness, with reduced variation in acousticness, as shown by the predominance of blue squares. The album also contains the most extreme, isolated feature changes: Sad Beautiful Tragic shows a substantial rise in instrumentalness, We Are Never Getting Back Together in speechiness, and Babe in duration, signaling highly targeted production adjustments. While a few songs feature faster tempos similar to Fearless, liveness generally decreases across the album, indicating that the tracks are more productionized.

Overall, the heatmap suggests that Fearless (TV) prioritizes boosting liveness and positivity, whereas Red (TV) tracks emphasize systematic enhancements in loudness and duration. These distinct approaches reflect each albums production philosophy, with some changes counterbalancing one another. For example, the increase in valence for Fearless versus the slight decrease for Red mirrors the broader trend of modest net change in emotional tone. Additionally, the global trend of increasing tempo appears to be heavily influenced by a few individual songs across both albums.

Research Question 2: In what ways do Taylor Swifts song features change across her career and fluctuate according to the time of year they are released?

We aim to understand how Taylor Swifts musical style has evolved over the course of her career and whether certain song characteristics vary depending on the time of year they are released. Specifically, we investigate patterns in raw audio features and assess whether these features exhibit long-term trends across albums or seasonal fluctuations within a year. Loudness was not included in the time-series analysis because it does not fall on the same scale as the other features. To begin, we averaged the remaining audio features across songs and plotted them as time series using track release dates, providing an overview of how her musical traits change over time and allowing us to identify both gradual trends and month-to-month variations.

The time-series graph illustrates how the audio features of Taylor Swifts songs evolve across her career. Several features, liveness, speechiness, and instrumentalness, remain consistently low and stable over time, indicating that these characteristics are not central components of her musical style and therefore exhibit minimal variation. Among the remaining features, energy and danceability show moderate volatility but no meaningful long-term trend. Both stay at relatively high levels across her discography, fluctuating primarily from album to album as she experiments with different moods and production styles, but without any sustained upward or downward movement. In contrast, valence and acousticness display the most pronounced and irregular fluctuations. Valence varies sharply between albums, reflecting shifts in emotional tone rather than a directional trend. These swings suggest that the mood of Taylors songs is closely tied to the thematic focus of each era rather than the progression of her career.

Acousticness shows the greatest variability of all features. Early in her career, acousticness is generally higher, consistent with her country-influenced beginnings, though it still fluctuates between albums. In the middle phase of her career, acousticness stabilizes at lower levels, aligning with her transition toward pop production. After 2020, acousticness rises dramatically and becomes highly volatile, with consecutive albums often showing opposite extremes. This pattern suggests purposeful experimentation where Taylor appears to be testing vastly different levels of acoustic elements across projects to match each albums concept and aesthetic. Overall, despite substantial fluctuations in valence and acousticness, there are no clear long-term trends in how these features evolve. The variations seem driven more by album-specific artistic choices than by a systematic shift over time.

Although some of Taylors audio features show no clear long-term trends, they may still exhibit seasonal patterns within each year. A feature can remain stable over time yet vary by season if the artist releases songs with different styles or moods that align with the time of year. In other words, Taylor may not undergo a consistent artistic shift over the years, but she might still favor certain genres, energies, or emotional tones during particular seasons. Given this possibility, our next step is to examine whether any audio features display within-year seasonality and whether Taylor tends to compose songs with distinct characteristics depending on the month or season of release.

The graph visualizes the average audio features of Taylor Swifts songs by release month. Liveness, speechiness, and instrumentalness remain relatively low and stable throughout the year, indicating that these features are generally consistent across her songs and show little dependence on release month. In contrast, danceability and energy exhibit higher variation and are positively correlated: songs with higher energy typically have strong beats, faster tempos, and driving rhythms, which also enhance danceability. Both features peak around the summer months, reflecting the tendency for artists to release upbeat, party-oriented tracks during this period, and decline toward winter when songs tend to be more moderate and lyric-focused.

Acousticness and valence display the greatest volatility across months. Valence shows no clear seasonal pattern but fluctuates more significantly between May and September, suggesting that songs released during these months vary widely in mood and emotional tone. Acousticness, meanwhile, is highly variable without apparent seasonal trends, indicating that Taylors use of acoustic elements depends more on artistic intent within specific albums than on the time of year.

Overall, while some features, particularly energy and danceability, show subtle seasonal variation, most audio characteristics (instrumentalness, liveness, valence) are consistent across release months, and acousticness fluctuates randomly. This suggests that, for Taylor Swifts songs, release month has limited influence on core audio features, with variation driven more by individual song or album choices than by season or year.

Research Question 3: How do Taylor Swifts albums differ and cluster together based on their overall audio characteristics?

We want to investigate the question of how do Taylor Swifts albums differ and cluster together based on their overall audio characteristics. In other words, we want to know if some albums share similar overall sound profiles across key audio features, and if the albums cluster into distinct stylistic groups such as acoustic/folk or pop.

To investigate how Taylor Swifts albums differ and cluster based on their overall audio characteristics, the analysis focuses on eight key Spotify audio features: danceability, energy, loudness, speechiness, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, and valence. These variables were chosen because together they provide a comprehensive quantitative representation of a songs musical texture, performance style, and emotional tone.

We first use a set of boxplots to show the distribution of each audio feature across Taylor Swifts albums. The purpose is to provide an initial exploratory overview of how musical characteristics vary both within and between albums.

The boxplots illustrate noticeable variation in audio features across Taylor Swifts albums, suggesting that each album exhibits distinct sonic characteristics. Albums such as folklore and evermore show higher acousticness and lower loudness and energy, reflecting their folk-inspired sound. In contrast, albums like 1989 and reputation demonstrate higher energy, loudness, and danceability, consistent with their pop production. The boxplots also show that instrumentalness and liveness dont change much between albums. This means that almost all of Taylor Swifts songs include vocals and were recorded in a studio rather than performed live.

The ANOVA results statistically confirm these visual trends. Most features, including danceability (p < 0.001), energy (p < 0.001), loudness (p < 0.001), speechiness (p < 0.001), acousticness (p < 0.001), and valence (p = 0.03), differ significantly across albums, supporting the conclusion that Taylor Swifts albums possess distinct audio profiles. Only instrumentalness and liveness were not significant (p > 0.05), aligning with the expectation that these traits remain relatively constant across her work.

After observing clear differences in individual audio features through the boxplots and ANOVA, a PCA biplot was used to explore how these features relate to each other in a single, multidimensional view. This method helps reveal broader patterns and clusters, showing which albums share similar sound profiles and which features drive those relationships.

The PCA biplot summarizes how Taylor Swifts albums relate to one another across all eight audio features at once. The first two principal components explain about 70% of the total variance (47.4% on Dim1 and 23.2% on Dim2), meaning they capture most of the differences in sound between albums.

From the PCA biplot, it is clear that albums like folklore and evermore appear on the upper-left side of the plot, aligning strongly with acousticness and slightly with instrumentalness, showing their softer, acoustic-driven production. In contrast, Speak Now, The Taylor Swift Holiday Collection, Fearless, and 1989 are positioned on the right, closely associated with energy, loudness, and liveness, reflecting their high-energy, pop-oriented sound. Red and Red (Taylors Version) sit near the center, bridging these two styles consistent with their mix of country-pop and more polished pop elements. Reputation sits at the very bottom of the biplot, aligning with danceability, which reflects its rhythmic production and electronic elements designed for movement. Lover and Midnights sit farther toward the bottom-left, aligning with speechiness, which reflects their lyrical delivery and conversational vocal style.

After examining individual features through boxplots and overall relationships through the PCA biplot, the dendrogram was employed to further explore how albums cluster based on their overall similarity in audio features. While the PCA shows these relationships in two-dimensional space, the dendrogram provides a hierarchical view, which groups albums step by step according to how similar their sound profiles are.

From the dendrogram, folklore and Evermore form the closest cluster, highlighting their shared acoustic and low-energy sound in indie-folk production. This tight pairing confirms their reputation as companion albums with cohesive emotional and sonic identities. On the left, Midnights and Reputation form a close cluster, indicating they share similar production qualities as both albums are characterized by darker tones and strong beats. Just above them, Evermore and Folklore join the same branch, showing that these four albums share overlapping but contrasting traits, but Folklore and Evermore introduces softer, acoustic textures. On the right side of the dendrogram, a second major branch includes 1989, Fearless, Fearless (Taylors Version), Speak Now, and Taylor Swift, which cluster together at relatively low dissimilarity levels. This grouping represents Swifts earlier and mid-career work, defined by a blend of country-pop and pop sounds. Further to the right, Lover, The Taylor Swift Holiday Collection, and the two Red albums form another related group. Lover bridges the gap between her pop and acoustic phases, while Red and Red (Taylors Version) show simular characteristics.

Together, the boxplots, PCA biplot, and dendrogram illustrate how Taylor Swifts albums differ and cluster based on their audio features, showing significant variation in attributes like energy, loudness, and acousticness.

Conclusion

Our main takeaways from this research are as follows: 1) The Taylors Version re-recordings show consistent production enhancements compared to the Originals, generally featuring higher loudness, greater energy, and tighter dynamic control, which multivariate analysis confirms as a shift toward a more consistent, smoother sonic profile. Album-specific analysis further reveals that these changes were tailored, with Fearless (TV) emphasizing liveness and valence, while Red (TV) focused on duration and loudness increases. 2) Across Taylor Swifts career, most musical features remain steady, with only valence and acousticness varying notably by album. Seasonal trends are minimal, showing slight summer peaks in energy and danceability but no strong release-time effects on overall sound. 3) With statistical tests and clustering confirming clear groupings that reflect her stylistic evolution across eras, Taylor Swifts albums have distinct sonic identities (where folk albums like Folklore and Evermore are softer and more acoustic, while Pop albums like 1989 and Reputation are louder and more energetic).

While the taylor_all_songs dataset provides a rich foundation for analyzing Taylor Swifts musical evolution, several limitations should be acknowledged. First, all audio characteristics, such as danceability, energy, and valence, are derived from Spotifys algorithms, which quantify musical traits based on computational models rather than human perception, potentially introducing biases in feature interpretation. Second, all lyrics values are recorded as NA, preventing any lyrical or thematic analysis alongside the audio data. Another limitation is that the dataset does not include listener metrics such as chart performance or streaming counts, which restricts the analysis to musical features alone without considering how these characteristics translate to popularity or audience response. Finally, the dataset does not include Taylor Swifts releases from 2023 onward, meaning the analysis cannot reflect her most current musical developments.

As a result, our report identifies several related questions that remain unanswered but could be addressed in future work. Incorporating lyrical data would enable semantic and thematic analyses, allowing us to examine how emotions, topics, and narrative structures evolve across Taylor Swifts career. Adding streaming or chart performance data would make it possible to study how musical attributes relate to commercial success and audience reception. Finally, access to more fine-grained and recent data, combined with advanced modeling techniques such as multilevel time-series models or feature engineering methods not covered in this course, would support a more complete investigation of how song characteristics interact with release timing and career stages.
